#let images = (
  "19.1": (
    caption: [Schematic drawing of a phytomer, the basic module of shoot organization in seed plants. The phytomer consists of an internode, a node, a leaf, and an axillary bud. This modular structure is repeated throughout the plant to build shoot architecture.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "19.2": (
    caption: [The gravitropic setpoint angle of tree branches creates different patterns of tree architecture. Different species have characteristic branch angles that contribute to their overall growth form, from upright to spreading canopies.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "19.3": (
    caption: [Long-distance transport of three types of hormones that regulate shoot branching: auxin, cytokinins, and strigolactones. Auxin is produced primarily in young expanding leaves and is transported basipetally by PIN1-mediated polar auxin transport. Strigolactones and cytokinins are synthesized mainly in the root and can be translocated acropetally to the shoot in the xylem. These two hormones can also be synthesized in shoot tissues adjacent to axillary buds.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "19.4": (
    caption: [Axillary bud outgrowth is inhibited by auxin and strigolactones. (A) Classic physiological experiments demonstrating the role of auxin in apical dominance. In de-tipped shoots the axillary buds begin to grow out, but auxin applied to the cut surface prevents outgrowth. Auxin transport inhibitors applied to the stem also release axillary buds from apical dominance. (B) Strigolactone biosynthesis mutants (max mutants) have increased shoot branching phenotype.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "19.5": (
    caption: [Hormonal network regulating apical dominance. Auxin from the shoot apex promotes strigolactone synthesis in the nodal area via the MAX4 gene. In eudicots, auxin up-regulates the BRANCHED 1 (BRC1) gene and down-regulates IPT genes. BRC1 inhibits axillary bud growth. Strigolactones also inhibit cytokinin biosynthesis, which otherwise would prevent BRC1 production.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "19.6": (
    caption: [Comparison of teosinte (Zea mays ssp. parviglumis) and modern maize (Zea mays ssp. mays). The reduced branching phenotype of maize compared to its highly branched ancestor teosinte is controlled by the TEOSINTE BRANCHED 1 (TB1) gene, which was a key target of domestication.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "19.7": (
    caption: [Types of dormant buds. (A) Dormant axillary buds of horse chestnut (Aesculus hippocastanum) surrounded by bud scales. (B) Diagram of sequential axillary buds, accessory buds, and secondary accessory buds showing different bud arrangements in the leaf axil.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "19.8": (
    caption: [Examples of different protoxylem and protophloem arrangements in eudicot roots. The diagram shows various patterns of xylem and phloem tissue arrangement in cross sections of roots, demonstrating diversity in vascular organization.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "19.9": (
    caption: [Lateral root development in Arabidopsis. (A) Longitudinal section of the primary root showing its developmental zones. The prebranch site, where a branch root will form if given the appropriate signals, forms after an oscillatory phase of auxin responsive gene expression within the oscillation zone. The oscillation zone confers competence on the xylem pole pericycle cells to differentiate into lateral root founder cells. (B) Cross section of primary root showing oscillating auxin responses occur in the protoxylem, with signaling to adjacent xylem pole pericycle cells. (C) Longitudinal sections showing stages of lateral root primordia development.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "19.10": (
    caption: [Prebranch sites form in the oscillation zone, immediately below the maturation zone. (A) Expression of the luciferase gene driven by the auxin-sensitive DR5 promoter in an Arabidopsis root showing auxin signaling levels that fluctuate over time in the oscillation zone (OZ). Asterisks indicate prebranch sites, which correspond to the auxin activity maxima. (B) Auxin signaling levels measured by luminescence in two Arabidopsis roots oscillate with a period of about 6 hours in the oscillation zone. (C) Auxin maxima along the root correspond to sites of bending, lateral root formation, and lateral root emergence.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "19.11": (
    caption: [Monocot root systems. (A) Root system of a 14-day-old maize seedling composed of primary root derived from the embryonic radicle, seminal roots derived from the scutellar node, postembryonically formed crown roots that arise at nodes above the mesocotyl, and lateral roots. (B) Mature maize root system showing the extensive fibrous root architecture typical of monocots.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "19.12": (
    caption: [Soybean root system showing primary root (taproot), branch roots, basal roots, and adventitious roots. This demonstrates the complex architecture of eudicot root systems with a dominant taproot and multiple orders of lateral roots.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "19.13": (
    caption: [Regulation of shoot gravitropic setpoint angles by IGT transcription factors. (A) The branch angles of an Arabidopsis tac1 mutant are more upright than those of the wild type (WT), while a lazy1/dro1 double mutant has more horizontal stem angles. (B) In rice, shoot and root growth angles are more horizontal in TAC1 overexpressors, demonstrating the role of these genes in controlling organ orientation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "19.14": (
    caption: [Internal anatomy of a woody stem. The vascular cambium (red region) consists of a single layer of cambial initial cells and its immediate derivatives on either side, and is surrounded by an outer layer of secondary phloem cells (black) and an inner layer of secondary xylem cells (light green). The primary phloem (dark blue), primary xylem (dark green), and pith (light blue) are also shown. The periderm includes the phellogen (tan cell layer), phelloderm (pink), and phellem (cork cells, in brown). The bark layer includes all tissues external to the vascular cambium, including the primary and secondary phloem.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "19.15": (
    caption: [Development of secondary vascular tissue. (A) Primary growth in woody stems occurs in the spring, followed by secondary growth. (B) Orientations of the cell division planes in the cambial zone maintain the proper balance between growth in diameter versus circumference. Cambial cells initially divide anticlinally to produce new initials and increase the circumference of the cambium. The same initials also divide periclinally to produce xylem and phloem mother cells, always leaving behind another initial.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "19.16": (
    caption: [Development of cambial tissue in roots. (A) In young roots, procambial cells separate protophloem and protoxylem, forming the vascular cylinder. In older roots, the vascular cambium is switched on to produce new phloem and xylem. (B) In older roots, xylem cells with high concentrations of auxin act as organizers of the vascular cambium, with HD-ZIP III proteins keeping them quiescent. Unknown signals travel from the initial cell organizer to adjacent cells to specify them as initial cells, which express ANT and divide to produce xylem on the inner side and phloem on the outer side.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "19.17": (
    caption: [Comparison of three distinct patterning processes that exploit regulatory interactions between small peptides and WOX class transcription factors. (A) WUS promotion of apical initials in the shoot apical meristem (SAM). (B) WOX5 promotion of initials in the root apical meristem (RAM). (C) WOX4 promotion of initials in the vascular cambium. These three systems share similar molecular mechanisms for maintaining stem cell populations.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "19.18": (
    caption: [Radial growth can be enhanced by modifying the expression of key transcription factors. (A) WOX4 and BP promote cambial proliferation and wood production, and this stimulation can be further enhanced in plants with mutations in PETAL LOSS (PTL), which encodes a MYB-like transcription factor that acts as a negative regulator of radial growth. LBD4 favors phloem formation. (B) Ruthenium red-stained cross sections of Arabidopsis roots of wild-type (WT) plants and plants overexpressing WOX4 showing much greater radial growth in the WOX4-OE/ptl root.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "19.19": (
    caption: [Hormones are involved in regulating key stages of secondary vascular tissue development. The protein ARABIDOPSIS HISTIDINE PHOSPHOTRANSFER PROTEIN 6 (AHP6) acts as a cytokinin signaling inhibitor that restricts the domain of cytokinin activity, thus allowing protoxylem differentiation in a spatially specific manner. Auxin and cytokinin interactions control vascular patterning.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "19.20": (
    caption: [Periderm formation in Arabidopsis roots. (A) Phellogen is a bifacial meristem that produces phellem (cork) on the outside and phelloderm on the inside. The periderm is formed from the pericycle, the outer layer of the vascular cylinder (stele). The diagram shows progressive stages of periderm development, including endodermis programmed cell death, cortex and epidermis sloughing, and formation of suberized cells.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "19.21": (
    caption: [Epicormic branches and bud. (A) Eucalyptus tree 2 years after the 2003 Eastern Victoria alpine bushfires in Australia, showing vigorous epicormic branch growth that allows the tree to recover after fire damage. (B) Epicormic bud of Tilia platyphyllos, covered by bark, representing dormant meristems that can be activated under stress conditions.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
)
